Installing and Configuring R and RStudio

Author

A. Jordan Nafa

Published

January 26, 2023

Important Note Regarding Chromebooks

If you have a Chromebook rather than a Windows or Mac computer, these installation instructions will not work. While there are ways to install R, RStudio, and other software on Chromebooks the process for doing so is different depending on what version of ChromeOS you have and may not be supported on older models. If this problem applies to you, please make an appointment or come by during office hours as soon as possible so we can figure out what the appropriate steps to get everything up and running are.

For the applied component of this courseâincluding all in-class examples, problem sets, and your final projects, we will be using the statistical programming language R, the lingua franca of applied statistics and a powerful tool for analyzing data in the social sciences and beyond. Alongside Python, R is widely used for data analysis in academia, the private sector, and certain government agencies.1 The purpose of this guide is to help walk you through the steps necessary to get R installed and configured on your personal computer.

Alternative Access Options for R and RStudio

I have made arrangements to ensure the latest versions of R, RStudio, and RTools are installed on the computers in the Political Science Lab in Wooten Hall 173. Unfortunately, I cannot guarantee recent versions of R, RStudio, or RTools are installed or available at other locations on the UNT campus. Please note the Political Science Lab in Wooten Hall 173 is only open from 8AM to 5PM, Monday-Friday. If this presents a problem with your schedule and you do not have other means of accessing current versions of R and RStudio, you may want to switch to a different section of this course.

Installing the base R Language

The first step in the installation process is to download and install the base language from the CRAN website. The latest version, 4.2.2 (2022-10-31, Innocent and Trusting), can be obtained by clicking the appropriate link for your operating system from those shown below. During the installation process, you can leave all of the installation options at their default and just click the ânextâ button in the bottom right corner of the installation window.

  • Windows 8, 10, 11

  • MacOS 10.13 (High Sierra) or later Intel 64-bit

  • MacOS 11 (Big Sur) or later Apple M1/M2

XQuartz for MacOS Users

If you downloaded either of the MacOS versions above, you also need to download and install XQuartz. This step is only for MacOS users.

Installing and Configuring RStudio

After completing the previous steps, you can now proceed to installing the latest version of RStudio, an integrated development environment (IDE) which provides a wide range of features for programming and technical writing in R, Quarto, and numerous other popular languages such as HTML, CSS, C++, Python, Stan, and javascript to name a few. To download the latest version of RStudio, click on the link below that corresponds to your operating system. During the installation process, you can just leave things at their default settings and click through the installation windows.

  • Download RStudio 2022.12.0+353 for Windows 10/11

  • Download RStudio 2022.12.0+353 for MacOS 10.15 and higher

Customizing and Configuring RStudio

Once you have installed RStudio, you can customize its appearance and the default behavior of many aspects of your R Sessions. Since some of the customization options covered below require the xfun package, you should start by executing the code below in the RStudio console before proceeding. Note this also demonstrates one of the ways we can install packages in R.

# Installing the xfun package
install.packages("xfun")

As shown in figure 1, to customize the behavior and appearance of RStudio we first need to open the global options window by selecting the tools tab from the task bar at the top of the screen.

Once weâve opened the global options window, we can then click on the appearance tab to see the customization options for the general appearance of the RStudio IDE such as those shown in figure 2. RStudio includes several different theme options by default, though you may also download a wide variety of others depending on your personal tastes.2

In addition to customizing the appearance of RStudio you can also customize its default behavior by selecting the âGeneralâ tab as shown below. For the purposes of this course, I recommend setting the default options for your RStudio sessions to those shown in figure 3 and leaving everything else at its default settings.

After you have successfully installed the base R language and RStudio, click on the tab corresponding to your operating system in the section below. Note that for more detailed information on the functionality of RStudio, you should also consult the following helpful resource which provides a general overview of the layout of the RStudio IDE.

  • RStudio IDE Cheatsheet

You can also consult the educational resources and helpful tutorials for beginners provided by the RStudio Foundation.

  • RStudio Educational Tutorials

R Tools and XCode

  • Windows
  • MacOS
Required Step

You will not be able to successfully complete the steps in the Stan installation tutorial without first installing Rtools. This is a required step for much of the code we will use throughout this course.

If you are on a Windows operating system, you will need to install Rtools 4.2 which can download by clicking on the hyperlink below. Rtools is required to install packages from source and, more importantly, anything that requires a C++ compiler, including though not limited to Stan.

  • Download Rtools 4.2

Once again, during the installation process you can just leave things at their default settings, especially in the case of the installation directory since changing its default locations may result in errors during package compilation. After you have completed this step, you will need to install the required packages by running the code below in order to successfully render the Quarto document for problem set 0. If you encounter errors when rendering the document, please ensure you have these packages installed.

# Installing packages required to complete problem set 0
install.packages(c(
  "pacman",
  "remotes",
  "tidyverse",
  "data.table",
  "dtplyr",
  "downlit",
  "xml2", 
  "rmarkdown", 
  "sessioninfo"
  ))
Required Package Installations

You must install these packages in order to successfully render the problem set documents for this course.

If you receive an error when attempting to load tidyverse, it is likely due to a bug in the dbplyr packageâa dependency of tidyverseârelated to a conflict with the CRAN version of Brobdingnag. To fix this you can run the following code which installs the development version of Brobdingnag from the packageâs github repository where the bug has been resolved.

# Installing a package from github using the remotes package
remotes::install_github("RobinHankin/Brobdingnag")

If you encounter issues with any of the above installation steps, please reach out to the teaching assistant or instructor for assistance as soon as possible. Do not put off getting R, RStudio, and RTools installed and configured since problem set 0 submissions after February 10th will receive a grade of 0. Putting this off until the last possible minute will be detrimental to your grade in this course.

Required Step

You will not be able to successfully complete the steps in the Stan installation tutorial without first installing Xcode. This is a required step for much of the code we will use throughout this course.

If you are on a MacOS operating system, you will need to install the Xcode developer tools. You can obtain the full MacOS development environment from the Apple AppStore using the link below. Xcode is required to install packages from source and, more importantly, anything that requires a C++ compiler, including though not limited to Stan.

  • Download Xcode from the AppStore

However, since downloading this can be extremely time consuming given the large size of the full development tools suite an alternative option is to install a paired down version that provides the tools necessary for our purposes in this course without the overhead of the full Xcode development environment. You can install the paired down version of Xcode by running the code below in the RStudio console.3

## MacOS Users may need to install the rstudioapi manually first
install.packages("rstudioapi")

## Run the command to install xcode-select
rstudioapi::terminalExecute(
  command = "xcode-select --install"
)
Note

If you run into issues installing Xcode using the code above you may need to open RStudio with administrator privileges in order to successfully complete the installation.

Once you have completed this step, you will need to install the required packages by running the code below in order to successfully render the Quarto document for problem set 0. If you encounter errors when rendering the document, please ensure you have these packages installed.

# Installing packages required to complete problem set 0
install.packages(c(
  "pacman",
  "remotes",
  "tidyverse",
  "data.table",
  "dtplyr",
  "downlit",
  "xml2", 
  "rmarkdown", 
  "sessioninfo"
  ))
Required Package Installations

You must install these packages in order to successfully render the problem set documents for this course.

Additional Installations

For our purposes in this course, I also suggest you install a citation management softwareâI personally use JabRef since it will export to any citation format in existenceâand the latest version of Quarto along with git. You can obtain each of these for your operating system by following the links below.

  • JabRef

    • Click âDownloadâ and select the appropriate version for your operating system. We will cover how to configure and use JabRef to organize sources during the second week of class.

  • Quarto

    • Download and install the appropriate version for your operating system.

  • git

    • If you are on Windows, download and install git. For those on MacOS, you will prompted to install git automatically upon opening RStudio for the first time. This will allow you to download and sync the courseâs github repository to your own computer and ensures your relative file paths are the same as mine, thus making it easier for me to assist you with any problems.

    • You can also make a github account, but this step is mostly optional. If you are interested in a job in tech, polling, data analytics, or graduate school in political science it can helpful to have a public portfolio demonstrating you know things related to the work in those industries and you can list a link to your github on your resume or CV. For a detailed introduction to git and R with RStudio, see the free online book Happy Git and GitHub for the useR

After installing git, you can run the following code from the console within RStudio to download the courseâs github repository

# Clone the course's github repository to your default directory
rstudioapi::terminalExecute(
    command = "git clone https://github.com/ajnafa/PSCI-3300-Political-Research-Methods-SP23.git",
    workingDir = getwd()
)

This will allow you to easily download content for the course throughout the semester.

Required Downloads

You will have a much more difficult time in this course if you choose not to clone the course repository. Working in this course folder ensures that your relative file paths are identical to those of the instructor and teaching assistant regardless of which operating system you are using.

Once you have successfully completed all of these steps you can proceed to the tutorial for installing and configuring Stan and brms! For useful resources on getting familiar with R syntax see the links below.

Resources for Learning R

  • Posit Primers

    • A series of interactive tutorials to help you become familiar with the syntax of R and the tidyverse

  • Hands-On Programming with R

    • A very, very basic introduction introduction to the fundamentals of programming in R and statistical programming concepts more broadly. Provides additional clarification for concepts introduced in R4DS that may be useful for those who have no background in programming.

  • R for Data Science

    • An open source online book that provides one of the best introductions to R and the tidyverse to date. I recommend reading through the workflow chapters at a minimum since they are reasonably short and cover important basic guidelines you will need to know for this course.
